{"/service/ndnp/mnhi/batch_mnhi_nimrod_ver01/data/sn86063381/00280767104/1921031601/1152.xml":{"full_text":"1\ntn\na\nnK\nnew\n|IIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIHIIIIIIIIIIIHIIIII|IIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIII|\n1 FROM MEN WHO KNOW 1\n1 W. P. G, HARDING, Governor of the\nSS Federal Resetfve Board: \"t?he country has recoveredl its nor\nmal state. We are no longer afraid. We are not indulging\nSB. in the old idea of extravagance, living beyond pur means. sss\nas Nor are we troubled so mucH as we were a e-vir weela ago ss:\n55 with the other extreme of oVfflPpessimism, where people get sss\nSS down in the dumps and they catinot see any daylight cannot gss\n5E see any hope see nothing but gloom and darkness. I say ss\nsss this in all candor: We are now looking forward to a year\nSE of constructive development. I want to say that intrinsically\ns there is no comparison today vt0h conditions a\nyeare\nSS when there was uneasiness and apprehension among1\ninformed over the badly expanded credit. Business is now\nrapidly reaching a new level and approaching a sound and\nsane basis. We have a better banking situation. We have\n.ss passed the danger point. We have a better understanding ESE\n55 of conditions.\"\nfl'\n1 ELBERT H. GARY, New York, Chair- 1\nSS man of Board, United States Steel Corporation: \"I am SS\nas hopeful and confident of the future as I have been at any\nSS time. Conditions are no worse than many months ago. The\n55 wonder is that they have not been much worse. Conditions\nare abnormal and even the minds of thoughtful people are'\nSS distorted. This, of course, is a result of the terrible time we\nSS have passed through. We have the spirit and determination\nto overcome all obstacles to the greatest success.\"\n1 CHARLES M. SCHWAB, New York, i\nSB Chairman of Board, Bethlehem SteeleCorporation: \"Out\npresent business depression ther will come a soundef\nbasis for the nation's activities and business will go forward\n\"IS with a buoyancy and force have never known befdre, as 3\nresult of reorganization,.we .,Tbe whole world during the S 3\nlast few years, has been a spendthrift and a waster. It has 3\nspent a large part of its liquid wealth and has now come to\na period where it can go fqrward only by energy and effort\nof the most vigorous kind. The only business foundations\n5 which are sure and steady are erected upon the rock of\neconomy.\"\n1 CHARLES MARKHAM, Chicago, 1\nSjS President, Illinois Central Railroad: \"There is every indi\ncatiobusinesswe\nthat shall enter shortly upon a period of increas-\nago,\nth best\nactivity in this country following the depres S S\nSS sion which resulted from what we haye come to designate SS\nthe 'buyers' strike.' The revival should have a wholesome\nreaction upon every, line of business which is founded upon\na real economic need, as are the railways and the lumber\ntrade. I believe the tide already is turninjt, and that we 5\nshall see it continue to strengthen during theliext epr weeks\nand months.\" :f i\nHON. HUGH M. CALDWELL, Mayor\nof Seattle, Washington: \"The shifting from the old year\nto the new finds the Pacific Northwest well equipped to face\nany emergency that may arise. Every substantial business\nSS man realizes that we are in the midst of a period of read\njustment that inevitably must run its course as a condition SS\nS precedent to better business and whether it runs fast or SS\nslowly, the final result will be the same.\"\n1 EDWARD COOKINGHAM, Port\nland, Ore., President, Ladd Tilton Bank: \"As to general\nconditions, it is quite certain that stocks of goods of all\nSS kinds are diminishing rapidly and I look for a better condi\ntion in almost all lines of trade and industry in 60 or 90\ndays. This will be especially so if our present income tax\nsss laws are properly revised so that industries will be relieved\nof the tremendous handicap of the excess profits tax.\"\nI R. S. HECHT, New Orleans, La., Presi\ndent, Hibernia Bank and Trust Co.: \"The year just closed\nhas been one of drastic readjustment. Our principal South\nera commodities have already suffered such a severe decline\nthat it seems reasonable to suppose the readjustment to\nS3 price levels is, nearly completed and that the worst is\nprobably over. Certain it is that whatever fluctuations we\nSS may have from now on will be within much narrower limits,\nand some hopeful signs for an improvement are not missing.\"\n1 M. JUSSERANpr French Ambassa- I\ndor to the United State?if \"The light of day is in front of\nus, gloom behind. FfrW$ jfcl# Jbleeding, ravaged, heavily\nladen, victorious nation of'France, like yours, has the right\nspirit. Thankful for ny belp that may come from abroad,\nand much has come from America, causing a gratitude which\nwill never cease, she intends to save herself to the best of\nher ability, and she wittj she has already begun.\"\n1 CHARLES SABIN, New York,\nSS President, Guaranty Trust Company: \"Those who are most\nclosely studying the existing situation feel that the turn of\nSS the tide in declining prices and liquidation is very near. Al-\nSS though there are many readjustments from the effects of the\nwar yet to be made in the months and years to come, th.ey ss,\nSS believe there is a reasonable assurance of a return to nor-\nSS mal business conditions, stabilized prices, easier money and -55\n55 larger business opportunities.\"\nIiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiii\n||r L.....\nMake it a year oipic spp3ndin||iy i#ihg wisely olthop\nneeded things fopioiiiiortlif selland home, thereby brinplg\nbusiness back to normalcy in sixty days.\nPrices Went Up a Step at a TimeThey Can't Come Down the Banister\nDo you realize what's happening? The\npublic is on a \"buying strike.\" A \"buy\ning strike\" to a nation is what a \"hun\nger strike\" is to an individual. Busi\nness is languishing today and why\nBecause demand has fallen off? No,\nsir! Because there is lack of capital\nto carry on? Not at all. The demand\nis there, but you are stifling it. The\nUnited States and Canada have ample\ncapital, and plenty of labor eager to\nwork. The public is like a moody, prosperous\nindividual, hanging around the house\nwith money in his pocket, wanting lots\nof things, needing lots of things but\nharboring an obsession that he won't\nspend his money-till prices come down\nto where they were six years ago.\nPrices didn't go up in a day. They can't\ncome down in a day. Prices went up\ngradually from 1914 to 1919. Prices\nwent up a step at a time. They can't\ncome down by the'banister. They must\ncome down the same way they went\n\"P.\nThe reason we were able to finance\nthe war so well Was because business\nlr 1ir rr rrM 1\nWhat is needed in this country more\nthan any other one thing today is con\nfidencewe have the money and the\nresources. The whole world has been\nundergoing this period of readjust\nment, as all inflation must be done\naway with and a'dollar will then be\nworth one hundred cents.\nLabor is beginning to realize that a\n\"day's pay demands a day's work\"\nand inefficiency and indifference, to\ngether with slacking, will no ldnger\nbe tolerated. Profiteering as prac\nticed during the high markets w^ill not\nbe tolerated either.\nWith capital willing to take a reason\nably fair profit with labor realizing\nits responsibility, all we need is co-op\neration on the part of the buying pub\nlic to make business as usual.\nConservative buying* should be uni\nversally practiced. Extravagance and\nuseless spending should not be in\ndulged in. It is the duty of everyone\nibnniMHiiummmiMH\nI This page is appearing in 450\ncities in the United States and\nCanada under the auspices of\nthe Local Kiwanis Clubs.\nBaer, H. C, State Bank\nBagley, A. M.. Wood, JRallroad Supplies\nBailey, T. C, Lawyer.\nBilker, G. T.. Jeweler.\nBerman, E. B., Insurance.\nBoardman. R, .T.. Pharmacist.\nBorreson. Dr. B.. Physician.\nBowser. W. X.. Pry Goods.\nBrooks, W, L.. National Banker.\nBurke. T. J.. Wholesale Grocer.\nCarson, G. K.. Newspaper Publisher.\nChifTv. John, Cedar Posts. Polos, Ties\nCulver. J. M.. Public Utilities.\nDahlberg. R. H.. Traffic Manager, Cx. Lumber Co.\niDannenberg, Dr. A., Chironracfcv.\nPenison. Dr. XV. K.. Veterlnatrian.\nPoran, A., Meats.\nPuxbury. F. U.. Real Estate.\nTCIwell. L. J.. State Ban*.\nlErvin. T. S., Wholesale Klour, Feed and Grain.\nFraser, F. H.. Merchant Tailor.\nGeorjre, .1. U. Gas Manufacturer.\nwas goodpeople bought and sold.\nThe only way we cari PAY for the\nwar is by buying and sellingtrad\ning And, moreover, prices are down\nfor many commodities they are al\nready down to lower levels than- they\nshould bethings are selling for less\nthan they cost to make. That is an\nimpossible situation. If you won't buy\nthe things the other fellow makes, HE\ncan't buy. the things you make. That\nis reasonable, is it not? And if he\ndoesn't buy the things you make, the\nshutters will soon be up on your place\nof business. Those who are insistently\ndetermined to wait until things\n\"crash\" before they buy are not do\ning humanity a service. For nobody\ncan sell things long at a loss.\nThe prices of overcoats, shoes, furni\nture, tires and, in fact,! all other com\nmodities are based on the cost of raw\nmaterial, labor, freight, etc., and prof\nit to those who make, handle and sell\nthem.\nYour livelihood and prosperity are\nbound up in the livelihood and pros\nperity of other menyou can't deny\n^^lia^^^fc^^^^^l^i^^l^^^^^^^lllhl*^^^*^^fci^^Illl^^ll^^**^^^^^^'^^^^*'**\n\"If I can have with me in my work and life the spirit of Kiwanis, with its friendly co-op-\neration, I shall have no fear of the morrow. Your motto, 'We Build,' is the greatest thing\nin the world, but we must not only build, but preserve. I have been trying to organize a\nlittle Kiwanis club of my own. There are to be onlyten members,rbut I am practicing the\nvery thought which you have in your own organization. I am trying to pick an outstand-\ning leader in each line for the ten. places in my Cabinet.\" Warren G. Harding, Presi-\ndentelect of the United States, Member of Marion, Ohio, Kiwanis Club.\nTh. Kiwani Mott- Is^'We Build\"lli\nand in the interest of all and for their\nown interest to buyand buy NOW.\nIn this way confidence will be created\nand it will stimulate business as noth\ning else will.\nYou should buy from the merchants\nthe merchants from the jobbers the\njobbers from the manufacturers. The\nmanufacturers would then be able to\ngive employment to thousands of\nworkmen and could purchase their\nraw material from the farms, mills\n#nd the mines, arid thus give employ\nment to thousands of other employees,\nand these employees would then buy\nfrom the merchants, and soan end\nless chain.'\nOur country has more money at pres\nent than ever before in its history and\nall that is needed to make business is\nconfidence. The whole world has been\nthrown into a near panic and we have\nsuffered business depression, and mat\nters have been made infinitely worse\nKIWANIS CLU OF BEMIDJI MINN.\nntmiiimii iiiiiii\n:-:^%-j\n.j.'\nGarlock, Dr. A., Sureon, Eye, Ear, Nose and\nThroat.\nCilbertson. J. L., Box Manufacturer.\nGilmore. Dr. ft.. Surgeon.\nOiven, N. K., Hardware.\nMven B. L.. Manager Turpentine Plant.\nOoURhnour, F. W.. Garage.\nHarding, G. S., Theater.\nHarker, R. V., Plumfcer\nHuffman. C. A., Furniture.\nHuffman, H. L., Lawyer.\nHughes, T., Elevator,\n-lerrard, E. V. Oil Company,\n.lewett. W.. Automobile Dealer.\nJohnson, A. C, Lumberman.\nJohnson, A. TX. County Official.\nKoors, F. J.. Bakery.\nLakin. B. W., Superintendent Croobston Lum. Co.\nUangdon. F. \\V.. Bottling Works.\nKreatz, G. E., Contractor.\n\"Laliberte. W. R Druggist.\nLycan. F. S., Hotel.\nthat point. There\" is nothing funda\nmentally wrong, with the country\nwe have bountiful crops, ample money,\ncapable heads and hands. But we\ncan't survive a \"buying strike\" never\ntheless. Business is a gigantic organ\nization, kept alive and active by trade\ncoursing through its veins. When\ntrade stops circulating, business dies.\nYour particular trade can't flourish\nin splendid isolation. The articles you\nmake can't be sold to men \"out of a\njob.\" True thrift is always wise, but\na stubborn refusal on the part of the\npublic to buy the things they need\nNOW is simply slowing down the\nwheels of commerce that feed and\nclothe and house us ALL.\nIf you are on a buying strike, \"forget\nit.\" Go out and buy today the things\nyou need, for the prices are down. If\nyou are waiting for them to come down\nfurther tomorrow or next day or next\nmonth, you may not THEN be in a\nposition to buy.\nReproduced by permission of Smith, Denne\nMoore, General Advertising Agents, Toronto\nand Montreal.\nil\n^l^^^^^l\nlll^,\nHMIMMIHUHM\nby \"calamity howlers,\" but our trou\nbles are largely psychological. What\nwe need is confidence and conserva\ntive optimism, coupled with the de\ntermination to go ahead. Can we do\nthis? I say we can. Let-everybody\npull together and don't wait for\nGeorge to do it/ When? RIGHT\nNOW. If you don't buy, you can't expect the\nnext fellow to, buy-j-and\nWhat's the resuit\nPoorhe business!won't\n?r,\nthousands of failures, hundreds of\nthousands of unemployed, hard times\nfor everyone. What's the remedy?\nBUY NOW! Buy your full normal\npurchase of the essentials, butBUY!\nIf you don't buy essentials now, you're\nhelping to create business disaster, for\nprices will come down with a thud.\nIf you do buy now, prices which have\nalready been lowered will continue to\ncome downbut slowly and safely to\nyour business and the country's busi\nness.\nJ. Mercer Barnett\nPRESIDENT,\nKIWANIS INTERNATIONAL\nLycan, R. B., Hotel.\nMarCum. W., Publisher,\nMarcum, Dr. E. H.-, Surgeon.\nMcCann, Dr. D., Physician.\nMitchell, rt S.\" Life Insurance.\nMitchell. H. Z.. Publisher.\nMoore. D. J.. Life Insurance.\nXaylor. A. J.. Electric-Retail Dealer.\nNeilson, C, Creamery Manager, t.\nXetzer, E. F.. Bottllno- Works.\nPalmer, Dr. G. M., Orthodentist.\nPhilippe, Fr. J. T., Clergy.\nRipple. E. .1.. Printer\nReynolds, H., Fire Insurance.\nRichardson. Dr. R. E.. Dentist.\nRobinson. W. 2.. Agricultural.\nStanton, Dr. P. L., Dentist.\nVendersluis. C. W.. Hardware.\nWarford, Rev. L. P.. Minister.\nAVhaley. O., Moving Picture Theater Manager.\nWhitman, D., Department Store.\n\"Wilson, S. S., Ladies' Ready to Wear.\nW","height":"26846","width":"21384"}}
